At Rome the authority of the emperor had auciently so much in· fluence in the creation of a bishop, that Gregory speaks of himself as having been appointed to the govemmeut of the Church by the sole command os the emperor, notwithstanding he had been formally chosen by the people. But the custom was, that when any one had been chosen by the senate, clergy, and people‚ 1t was immediately reported to the emperor, that he might either ratify the election by his approbation, or rescind it by his negative. Nor is there any thing repugnant to this custom in the decrees collected by Gratian; which only say, that it is by no means to be suffered that a king should supersede all ca- nonical election by appointing a bishop at his own pleasure, and that the metropolitana ought not to consecrate any one who shall thus have been promoted by the violence of power.
